3.3. Protein Supplementation Characteristics
Protocols for PS are summarized in Table 1, and the supplement program of each included RCT is
detailed in Table S3. The protocol for PS varied widely across the included trials. Regarding the amount
of protein, the majority of the included RCTs provided PS daily with amounts of extra protein ranging
from 4.1 to 40.8 g/day [
]. Twelve RCTs provided supplements before or
after exercise on training days with amounts of extra protein ranging from 6.0 to 41.4 g/session [
The protein source of the supplementation differed among the included studies and comprised
milk-based beverages, fortiﬁed milk, and milk protein concentrate [
]; a combination
of whey protein, leucine, and essential amino acids [
]; and dairy through diet [
]. Supplements were provided daily in most included RCTs [
whereas 12 RCTs provided an additional PS immediately before or after exercise on training days [26,
]. In 10 RCTs, the control group received a placebo supplement or diet [
], and in the remaining 12 included RCTs, the control group was subjected to
exercise sessions only without placebo supplement intake [
] (Table S3).
Fourteen of the 22 the included RCTs reported compliance for PS in their participants, most of
which reported well compliance for supplementations (80–100%) [
], with
the exception of one RCT reported a low compliance rate of 61% [43].
3.4. Exercise Training Protocol
A summary of protocols for exercise training is presented in Table 1, and the exercise regime
of each included RCT is detailed in Table S4. Participants in six RCTs received RET only [
] with an intensity of 50% to 80% of one repetition maximum (or OMNI-Resistance Exercise
Scale > 7), whereas those in other 15 RCTs received MET with moderate to high intensity [
]; the remaining one RCT which employed a pedometer-based walking program for
the frail community-dwelling older adults was categorized as MET subgroup [
]. The MET were
composed of resistance training [
], aerobic training [
], balance
training [
], and functional mobility training [
]. Eight
RCTs used a long-period exercise duration of 24 weeks or longer (48–168 sessions) [
56,58,60], eight RCTs used a medium-period treatment duration of 12–24 weeks (24–48 sessions) [44,
], and the other six RCTs used a short-period intervention of less than 12 weeks
(22–35 sessions) [
]. Thirteen RCTs involved whole-body training (upper and lower
extremities and trunk) [
], whereas the other nine involved training of only
lower extremity (Table S4) [
]. Compliance to RET was reported with an attendance
rate of 84–100% and 71–97% in frail community-dwellers [
] and nursing-home residents [
56], respectively; the attendance rates responding to MET were reported as 63–100% and 71–100% in
frail community-dwellers [
] and nursing-home residents [
], respectively; 6
of 22 included RCTs did not reported compliance to exercise intervention [47,50,53–55,60].
3.5. Risk of Bias in Included Studies
The individual PEDro scores are listed in Table 2. Of the 22 included RCTs, the methodological
quality of 11 was classiﬁed as high [
] and that of the other 11 as
medium [26,41,42,46,47,50,51,53,56,59,60], with a median (range) PEDro score of 7/10 (4/10 to 9/10).
The interrater reliability associated with the cumulative PEDro score was acceptable with an intraclass
correlation coefﬁcient of 0.96 (95% CI: 0.93–0.99). Of the 22 included RCTs, all incorporated random
allocation, similarity at the baseline, between-group comparisons, and point estimates and variability;
in addition, ﬁve incorporated concealed allocation, 11 incorporated subject blinding, 6 incorporated
therapist blinding, 10 incorporated assessor blinding, 14 incorporated adequate follow up, and 14
incorporated intention-to-treat analysis.
